APT Package Search

The [bold cyan]apt[/bold cyan] command provides several ways to find and inspect packages.

[dim]# Search for packages[/dim]
[bold green]$[/bold green] [bold]apt search[/bold] [yellow]keyword[/yellow]                [dim]# Search package names and descriptions[/dim]
[bold green]$[/bold green] [bold]apt search --names-only[/bold] [yellow]keyword[/yellow]  [dim]# Search package names only[/dim]

[dim]# Show package information[/dim]
[bold green]$[/bold green] [bold]apt show[/bold] [yellow]package[/yellow]                  [dim]# Show detailed package info[/dim]
[bold green]$[/bold green] [bold]apt-cache policy[/bold] [yellow]package[/yellow]          [dim]# Show available versions and sources[/dim]

[dim]# Explore dependencies[/dim]
[bold green]$[/bold green] [bold]apt depends[/bold] [yellow]package[/yellow]               [dim]# Show what a package depends on[/dim]
[bold green]$[/bold green] [bold]apt rdepends[/bold] [yellow]package[/yellow]              [dim]# Show what depends on a package[/dim]

[dim]# Find files in packages[/dim]
[bold green]$[/bold green] [bold]apt-file search[/bold] [yellow]path[/yellow]              [dim]# Find which package provides a file[/dim]
[bold green]$[/bold green] [bold]apt-file list[/bold] [yellow]package[/yellow]             [dim]# List all files in a package[/dim]

[yellow]Note[/yellow]: [bold]apt-file[/bold] requires installation and an initial database update ([dim]apt-file update[/dim]).
